    localAngle: `<h2>Calgary Hard Water and Your Dishwasher</h2>
<p>Calgary draws roughly two-thirds of its municipal water from the Bow River and one-third from the Elbow River, and both sources carry significant dissolved limestone from the Rocky Mountain headwaters. Independent municipal data puts Calgary water hardness in the 130-180 mg/L range comfortably inside the "very hard" classification. For a dishwasher, that translates to a slow but constant deposition of calcium carbonate scale on every surface that touches water: the heating element, the spray arm nozzles, the inlet valve solenoid, and the recirculating pump impeller.</p>
<p>The practical impact in a typical Calgary household: dishwashers tend to hit their first real failure between year three and year five earlier than the national average of seven to nine years. Spray arm rotation slows as nozzles clog, wash performance drops, and the heating element over-cycles trying to compensate. Eventually the high-limit thermal fuse trips and the cycle aborts mid-wash. We see this pattern in Bosch SHE-series, KitchenAid KDFE/KDPE, Samsung DW80, and Whirlpool WDT/WDF models almost every week.</p>
<p><strong>What actually works for Calgary dishwashers:</strong> First, set the rinse aid dispenser to the highest level level 5 or 6 on most brands. Calgary water needs the surfactant boost. Second, run a monthly hot cycle with two cups of plain white vinegar in a measuring cup on the top rack, with no detergent and nothing else in the machine. The acid dissolves carbonate scale before it bonds. Third, every six months, remove the lower spray arm, soak it in vinegar for an hour, and use a toothpick to clear each nozzle individually. Fourth, check the inlet hose screen at the back of the machine Calgary water deposits sediment there faster than anywhere else in Canada we service.</p>
<p>If your dishwasher is already showing symptoms of scale damage, descaling alone will not reverse mechanical wear. We carry the Affresh and Lemi-Shine commercial-strength descalers for situations where homeowner-grade products are not enough, and we replace components proactively when we see early-stage scale damage during a service visit. A single $180 spray arm replacement now usually prevents a $340 wash motor failure six months later.</p>`,
