    localAngle: `<h2>Calgary Altitude, Natural Gas, and Why Your Burners Behave Differently Here</h2>
<p>Calgary sits at roughly 1,045 metres above sea level high enough that gas combustion characteristics are noticeably different from sea-level design specifications. This is not just trivia; it directly affects how your gas stove performs and how long components last.</p>
<p>At Calgary altitude, atmospheric pressure is roughly 13.5% lower than at sea level. That means there is less oxygen per cubic foot of air drawn into the burner, so the flame runs slightly richer (less oxygen relative to fuel) than the burner was designed for. Manufacturers that sell into the Alberta market generally compensate by either supplying altitude-specific orifices or by tuning the air shutter wider, but this is not always done correctly at installation. We see Calgary gas stoves that have been running rich for years yellow flame tips, soot accumulation around burner ports, and elevated CO output that sets off the kitchen detector but never gets diagnosed.</p>
<p>The second Calgary-specific factor is natural gas pressure stability. ATCO Gas distribution maintains supply pressure at a regulated value, but the in-home pressure at your stove can dip when other appliances cycle on. A typical Calgary new build with high-efficiency furnace, water heater, and gas range can see momentary pressure dips during severe cold spells when all three appliances cycle on simultaneously. Modern stoves with electronic ignition handle this fine, but older standing-pilot units and budget electronic-ignition models can experience burner extinction events during these dips. We see this pattern consistently across older Calgary character homes in Inglewood, Bridgeland, and Hillhurst where gas ranges from the early 2000s are still in service.</p>
<p>The third factor is hardness in the gas itself not water hardness, but trace components in the natural gas distribution stream. Alberta natural gas contains small amounts of mercaptan (added for odour) and trace hydrocarbons that, over years of use, deposit a thin film on burner orifices and spark electrodes. This deposit slowly chokes burner ports and reduces spark intensity. We routinely service Calgary gas burner orifices every 4-5 years for cleaning, even when no specific complaint exists, because preventative cleaning extends component life and improves combustion efficiency.</p>
<p><strong>Calgary gas stove maintenance that prevents the major failures:</strong> First, every six months, lift the burner caps and clean the ports with a thin wire or pin never a toothpick (which can break off and lodge). Second, wipe the spark electrodes with a dry cloth at the same interval; oil and food residue conducts at low voltages and reduces spark energy. Third, listen to the burner ignition pattern if you hear delayed ignition (a "whoosh" instead of a clean light), schedule service before it gets worse. Fourth, if you renovated your kitchen and reused an existing gas range from a previous home, verify altitude orifices were swapped if the previous installation was below 600 metres. Fifth, never let boil-over liquids dry on burner heads they carbonize and create permanent ignition issues. Sixth, if you smell gas at any time, even faintly, treat it as a real leak: shut off the appliance valve and call us. We carry electronic combustible gas detectors and can pressure-test the appliance to leak-localize within 30 minutes.</p>
<p>One more important note for Calgary households with high-end gas ranges (Wolf, Viking, Thermador, Bertazzoni, La Cornue): these brands use brass burner components that respond differently to Calgary's gas profile. We are trained on the brand-specific service procedures, and we can re-jet for altitude correctly when units are imported or moved to Calgary from lower elevations.</p>`,
